aws::graph::propositions: # Zodiac 601XLB Aircraft Accident at Cabool Memorial Airport
An experimental amateur-built Zodiac 601XLB with registration N601ND was involved in an accident near Cabool Memorial Airport.
The accident occurred on February 29, 2020, at 1534 central standard time.
The pilot and passenger were uninjured in the accident.
The airplane was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.
The cockpit suddenly filled with black smoke after departing Cabool Memorial Airport.
The engine sputtered after the cockpit filled with black smoke.
The engine ceased operating after sputtering.
The pilot attempted to return to Cabool Memorial Airport.
The pilot landed the aircraft in a field short of the runway.
The airplane sustained substantial damage to both wings.
Postaccident examination of the engine revealed the No. 1 cylinder piston was broken in two pieces.
Postaccident examination of the engine revealed the piston crank link was bent.
The reason for the engine failures was unknown.
The pilot held a Commercial certificate.
The pilot was 84 years old and male.
The pilot had an Airplane Rating for Single-engine land.
The pilot occupied the left seat during the flight.
The pilot had no Other Aircraft Rating(s).
The pilot used a 3-point restraint system.
The pilot had an Instrument Rating for Airplane.
No second pilot was present during the flight.
The pilot had no Instructor Rating(s).
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot had no Medical Certification.
The pilot was not an Occupational Pilot.
The pilot's last Flight Review or Equivalent was on February 23, 2020.
The pilot had 4024 total flight hours in all aircraft.
The pilot had 165 total flight hours in the Zodiac 601XLB make and model.
The pilot had 3976 hours as Pilot In Command in all aircraft.
The pilot had 8 flight hours in the last 90 days in all aircraft.
The pilot had 6 flight hours in the last 30 days in all aircraft.
The pilot had 2 flight hours in the last 24 hours in all aircraft.

# Factual Information

## History of Flight

Enroute | Powerplant sys/comp malf/fail (Defining event)
--- | ---
Enroute | Unknown or undetermined
Enroute | Loss of engine power (total)
Emergency descent | Off-field or emergency landing
Landing | Collision during takeoff/land

On February 29, 2020, at 1534 central standard time, an experimental amateur-built Zodiac 601XLB, N601ND, was involved in an accident near Cabool Memorial Airport (TVB), Cabool, Missouri. The pilot and passenger were uninjured. The airplane was operated as a Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 personal flight.

According to the pilot, the cockpit "suddenly" filled with black smoke after departing TVB. The engine then sputtered and ceased operating. He attempted to return to TVB but landed in a field short of the runway. The airplane sustained substantial damage to both wings.

Postaccident examination of the engine revealed the No. 1 cylinder piston was broken in two pieces, and the piston crank link was bent. The reason for the failures was unknown.
